American coach Randy Waldrum said he was not oblivious of the unfolding intensity in women’s African football competition as the Super Falcons face off against their Ivorian counterparts , Lady Elephants in the decisive final rounds towards a place at the 2022 Africa Women Cup of Nations ti be held later this year in Morocco. African champions, Super Falcons host the first leg at the Moshood Abiola National Stadium in Abuja on Friday with the reverse fixture fixed for 23rd February at the Stade Robert Champroux in Abidjan. “ We are preparing well for our next game against Cote d’Ivoire and we understand they’re very good team ; we are very familiar with them and we respect the fact that on any given day if you’re not prepared to play, they are a team that can cause problems for us,” the 65-year-old Waldrum told NationSport.   Adesanya targets ‘fresh meat’ after historic…     EPL: Conte’s Tottenham Hotspur lose to Wolves 0-2     Trippier’s free-kick clears Newcastle from relegation…   “ But he big picture for us as a country is that we feel like we have all the talent, we feel like we have a great team and a great support from a federation . “ Always, our style will be about attacking football and that’s the way we will approach the game (against the lady Elephants) whether it is in Abuja or it’s in the Ivory Coast (Abidjan). - Advertisement - “ We want to play an attacking football ; we want to be on the front foot, we want to control the game and forced them to play out of their comfort zone ,” hinted the vastly experienced Waldrum who doubles as the women’s head coach of University of Pittsburgh . Meanwhile, our correspondents gathered last night that the Ivorian contingent for Friday’s big match is expected in Abuja today. SPONSORED